Ordinary Differential Equations


Yuji Saikai
ysaikai@unimelb.edu.au
School of Mathematics and Statistics
The University of Melbourne

These notes are based on Chapter 13 of JMR Jones, O., Maillardet, R., & Robinson, A. (2014). Introduction to scientific programming and simulation using R (2nd ed.). CRC Press.

Introduction

Recall that solving a system of ordinary differential equations (ODEs) \[ \frac{d}{dt}\mathbf{y}(t) = \mathbf{f}(\mathbf{y}(t)) \] means finding a function \(\mathbf{y}(t)\) that satisfies the system of equations.

In differential equations, notations can easily get confusing. In these notes, I explicitly use boldface to denote vectors and vector-valued functions (e.g., \(\mathbf{y}\) and \(\mathbf{f}\)).

We consider only autonomous systems, that is, the right-hand side depends on \(t\) only through \(\mathbf{y}(t)\).

We use as a running example the predatorprey model, which is based on the Lotka-Volterra equations.

Predatorprey model

The predator-prey model is used to describe the population dynamics of two species, the one as a predator and the other as a prey. The model consists of a pair of ODEs: \[\begin{align} \frac{dy_1}{dt} &= ay_1 - by_1y_2\\ \frac{dy_2}{dt} &= gby_1y_2 - ey_2 \end{align}\] where

  • \(y_1\) : prey population
  • \(y_2\) : predator population
  • \(a\) : natural growth rate of prey in the absence of predation
  • \(b\) : death rate due to the predation
  • \(g\) : birth rate of predator due to the captured prey
  • \(e\) : natural death rate of predator.

The system is known to have periodic solutions, which do not allow simple expressions. Fortunately, it is still easy to obtain an implicit equation of \(y_1\) and \(y_2\). Eliminating \(dt\) from the above system of ODEs, we have: \[\begin{alignat}{2} &&(ay_1-by_1y_2)dy_2 &= (gby_1y_2-ey_2)dy_1\\ &\Leftrightarrow\quad &\int \frac{a-by_2}{y_2}dy_2 &= \int \frac{gby_1-e}{y_1}dy_1\\ &\Leftrightarrow\quad & c &= gby_1-e\log(y_1)+by_2-a\log(y_2) \end{alignat}\] where \(c\) is a constant. With \(a=0.05\), \(b=0.0002\), \(g=0.8\), \(e=0.03\), and \(c=-0.3\), we have the following orbit in a phase space.

a <- 0.05
b <- 0.0002
g <- 0.8
e <- 0.03
c <- -0.3
y1 <- seq(0, 800, length=1000)
y2 <- seq(0, 830, length=1000)
out <- outer(y1, y2, function(y1,y2) g*b*y1 - e*log(y1) + b*y2 - a*log(y2) )
contour(y1, y2, out, levels=c, xlab=bquote("prey" ~ (y[1])), ylab=bquote("predator" ~ (y[2])))
from_x <- c(16.05, 400, 500)
from_y <- c(401, 48, 652.3)
to_x <- c(16, 401, 499)
to_y <- c(400, 48.1, 653)
y0 <- c(150, 804)
points(y0[1], y0[2],pch=16)
text(y0[1], y0[2]-50, expression(y[0]), pos=4)
arrows(from_x, from_y, to_x, to_y, length=.1)
title("Periodic orbit in the predator-prey model")

Just as we can find closed-form antiderivatives only in special integration problems, we can find analytical solutions only for special types of ODEs. Again, numerical methods allow us to (approximately) solve a wider class of problems.

Numerical solutions

As nonsensical as it sounds, if we knew \(\mathbf{y}(t)\) on the right-hand side of the above ODEs, a solution would be a usual integral with respect to \(t\): \[\mathbf{y}(t) = \int \mathbf{f}(\mathbf{y}(t))dt .\] But, of course, we do not know \(\mathbf{y}(t)\), which is the point of this exercise. Nevertheless, when we work on an initial value problem \[ \mathbf{y}(h) = \mathbf{y}(0) + \int_0^h \mathbf{f}(\mathbf{y}(t))dt , \] such a nonsensical integral gives us a reminder that solving a differential equation is doing integration. Then, you remember that, almost always, whether it is analytical or numerical integration, when it is hard, we approximate the integrand by a simple function.

In analytical integration, an integral is defined as a limit. So, it does not matter whether we approximate the integrand by a function or constant values. In numerical integration, on the other hand, the choice of simple functions affects the performance of approximation because we always have to settle for finite granularity depending on our computational capacity.

Recall the techniques used in Numerical Integration, where we approximate a complex function over each subinterval by simple functions so that we can carry out an integral with ease. Specifically, linear functions in the trapezoidal rule and quadratic functions in Simpsons rule. Why not applying the same idea here approximating an unknown function \(\mathbf{y}(t)\)?

Besides the similarity, also note the difference. In the standard numerical integration, we can evaluate the function wherever we like. In contrast, here, we can evaluate only the derivative \(\frac{d\mathbf{y}}{dt} = \mathbf{f}\) and evaluation points \(\{\mathbf{y}(t)\}\) themselves depend on our preceding approximations.

Eulers method

Lets try linear approximation because its derivative is a constant and easy to integrate. Let \(\hat{\mathbf{y}}(t)\) be an approximation to \(\mathbf{y}(t)\) for \(t>0\), and \(\hat{\mathbf{y}}(0) = \mathbf{y}(0)\). If \(\hat{\mathbf{y}}(t)\) is linear, then \[ \mathbf{f}(\hat{\mathbf{y}}(t)) = \frac{d}{dt}\hat{\mathbf{y}}(t) \] is a constant. A natural choice is \[ \mathbf{f}(\hat{\mathbf{y}}(t)) = \mathbf{f}(\hat{\mathbf{y}}(0)) \] for all \(t\in[0,h]\), and we can easily compute \(\mathbf{f}(\hat{\mathbf{y}}(0))\) using the knowledge of \(\mathbf{f}\) and \(\hat{\mathbf{y}}(0) = \mathbf{y}(0)\). Thus, \[\begin{align} \hat{\mathbf{y}}(h) &= \hat{\mathbf{y}}(0) + \int_0^h \mathbf{f}(\hat{\mathbf{y}}(0))dt\\ &= \hat{\mathbf{y}}(0) + h\mathbf{f}(\hat{\mathbf{y}}(0)) \end{align}\]

Eulers method for numerically solving ODEs is to make the following repeated approximation until \(t=nh+h\): \[\begin{align} \hat{\mathbf{y}}(nh+h) &= \hat{\mathbf{y}}(nh) + \int_{nh}^{nh+h} \mathbf{f}(\hat{\mathbf{y}}(nh))dt\\ &= \hat{\mathbf{y}}(nh) + h\mathbf{f}(\hat{\mathbf{y}}(nh)) \end{align}\] for \(n\in\{0,1,\dots\}\).

Lets illustrate it using the predatorprey model. Each process starts at \(\mathbf{y}_0=(150, 804)\), which is a point on the orbit.

LV <- function(y) c(a*y[1] - b*y[1]*y[2], g*b*y[1]*y[2] - e*y[2])
euler <- function(f, y0, h, N) {
  Y <- matrix(nrow=N+1, ncol=length(y0)) # empty matrix
  Y[1,] <- y0 # R has 1-base indexing. Y[1,] for y0.
  for (n in 1:N) {
    Y[n+1,] <- Y[n,] + h*f(Y[n,])
  }
  return(Y) # returned value is a matrix
}
for (h in c(1, 0.1)) {
  N <- 880/h
  Y <- euler(LV, y0, h, N)
  plot(Y[,1], Y[,2], type='l', xlab=bquote("prey" ~ (y[1])), ylab=bquote("predator" ~ (y[2])))
  points(Y[1,1], Y[1,2])
  text(Y[1,1]+10, Y[1,2], expression(y[0]), pos=1)
  arrows(Y[N+1,1], Y[N+1,2],
         Y[N+1,1]+LV(Y[N+1,])[1], Y[N+1,2]+LV(Y[N+1,])[2],
         length=.1, lwd=2)
  title(paste("Euler's method (h = ", h, ")", sep=""))
}

While finer approximation with smaller \(h\) certainly produces smaller errors, even with \(h=0.1\), there is noticeable outward divergence from the orbit. Since our computational resources are often limited, we should not excessively rely on small \(h\). Hence, our task is to come up with better approximation of \(\mathbf{y}(t)\) to reduce errors without decreasing \(h\).

Remember that, when approximating \(\mathbf{y}(t)\), we make two decisions: linearity and its slope. Lets keep the linearity because it allows us to eliminate the dependency of the integrand \(\mathbf{f}(\hat{\mathbf{y}}(t))\) on \(t\in[nh,nh+h]\), thereby making the integral trivial. So, we try to engineer better slopes than the nave choice \(\mathbf{f}(\hat{\mathbf{y}}(nh))\).

\(\mathbf{f}\) is often called a vector field, a vector-valued function that tells the velocity of \(\mathbf{y}\) moving from \(\mathbf{y}(t)\) at \(t\). In these notes, to make clear association with linearity, such a velocity is called a slope.

Midpoint method

The midpoint method (a.k.a. the second-order RungeKutta) provides an intuitive approach to a better slope. The idea is simple: if \(\mathbf{y}(t)\) is a smooth function over \(t\in[nh, nh+h]\), then we expect the slope at the midpoint \(t=nh+h/2\) better captures the average dynamics than the slope at \(t=nh\). The following figure may help you get some intuition.

par(mar=c(0,0,0,0))
curve(-x^2, from=-.85, to=.2, ylim=c(-.75,.2), lwd=2,
      axes=FALSE, ann=FALSE, xaxt="n", yaxt="n")
x <- c(-.8, -.4, 0)
y <- c(-.64, -.16, 0)
points(x, y)
arrows(x[1], y[1], -.4, 0, length=.1, angle=12, lwd=1.2)
text(x[1], y[1]-.03, "y(nh)", pos=4, cex=1.5)
arrows(x[2], y[2], 0, y[2]+.32, length=.1, angle=12, lwd=1.2)
text(x[2], y[2]-.03, "y(nh+h/2)", pos=4, cex=1.5)
arrows(x[1], y[1], x[3], y[3], length=.1, angle=12, lwd=1.2)
text(x[3], y[3]+.03, "y(nh+h)", pos=4, cex=1.5)

To compute the slope at the midpoint \(\mathbf{f}(\hat{\mathbf{y}}(nh+h/2))\), we need to give \(\mathbf{f}\) the information \(\hat{\mathbf{y}}(nh+h/2)\), which we do not know. At this point, we give up and go back to Eulers method, i.e., \[\hat{\mathbf{y}}(nh+h/2) = \hat{\mathbf{y}}(nh) + \frac{h}{2}\mathbf{f}(\hat{\mathbf{y}}(nh)) .\] Lets review the idea of midpoint method.

  1. Eulers method can be improved by the midpoint method, which
  2. Computes \(\hat{\mathbf{y}}(nh+h)\) using \(\mathbf{f}(\hat{\mathbf{y}}(nh+h/2))\), which
  3. Requires \(\hat{\mathbf{y}}(nh+h/2)\), which is
  4. Computed by Eulers method.

Here is the idea in action.

midpoint <- function(f, y0, h, N) {
  Y <- matrix(0, nrow=N+1, ncol=length(y0))
  Y[1,] <- y0
  for (n in 1:N) {
    y.m <- Y[n,] + h/2*f(Y[n,]) # Euler for the midpoint
    Y[n+1,] <- Y[n,] + h*f(y.m)
  }
  return(Y)
}
for (h in c(10, 2)) {
  N <- 880/h
  Y <- midpoint(LV, y0, h, N)
  plot(Y[,1], Y[,2], type='l', xlab=bquote("prey" ~ (y[1])), ylab=bquote("predator" ~ (y[2])))
  points(Y[1,1], Y[1,2])
  text(Y[1,1]+10, Y[1,2], expression(y[0]), pos=1)
  arrows(Y[N+1,1], Y[N+1,2],
         Y[N+1,1]+LV(Y[N+1,])[1], Y[N+1,2]+LV(Y[N+1,])[2],
         length=.1, lwd=2)
  title(paste("The midpoint method (h = ",h,")", sep=""))
}

The result is dramatic improvement. Even with \(h=2\), it clearly performs better than Eulers method with \(h=0.1\).

Fourth-order RungeKutta

We can push the idea further to even better capture average dynamics. This time, the slope used in linear approximation is a weighted average of the following four slope estimates: \[\begin{align} \mathbf{k}_1 &= \mathbf{f}(\hat{\mathbf{y}}(nh))\\ \mathbf{k}_2 &= \mathbf{f}(\hat{\mathbf{y}}(nh)+\tfrac{h}{2}\mathbf{k}_1)\\ \mathbf{k}_3 &= \mathbf{f}(\hat{\mathbf{y}}(nh)+\tfrac{h}{2}\mathbf{k}_2)\\ \mathbf{k}_4 &= \mathbf{f}(\hat{\mathbf{y}}(nh)+h\mathbf{k}_3) \end{align}\]

\(\mathbf{k}_2\) is the one used in the midpoint method.

The fourth-order RungeKutta (RK4) computes \(\hat{\mathbf{y}}(nh+h)\) as follows: \[ \hat{\mathbf{y}}(nh+h) = \hat{\mathbf{y}}(nh) + h\left( \frac{1}{6}\mathbf{k}_1 + \frac{1}{3}\mathbf{k}_2 + \frac{1}{3}\mathbf{k}_3 + \frac{1}{6}\mathbf{k}_4 \right) .\]

These \(\mathbf{k}\)s and the associated weights are specifically constructed so that the lower-order errors in the Taylor approximation are cancelled out.

Here is the idea in action.

RK4 <- function(f, y0, h, N) {
  Y <- matrix(0, nrow=N+1, ncol=length(y0))
  Y[1,] <- y0
  for (n in 1:N) {
    k1 <- f(Y[n,])
    k2 <- f(Y[n,] + h/2*k1)
    k3 <- f(Y[n,] + h/2*k2)
    k4 <- f(Y[n,] + h*k3)
    Y[n+1,] <- Y[n,] + h*(k1/6 + k2/3 + k3/3 + k4/6)
  }
  return(Y)
}
for (h in c(10, 3)) {
  N <- 880/h
  Y <- RK4(LV, y0, h, N)
  plot(Y[,1], Y[,2], type='l', xlab=bquote("prey" ~ (y[1])), ylab=bquote("predator" ~ (y[2])))
  points(Y[1,1], Y[1,2])
  text(Y[1,1]+10, Y[1,2], expression(y[0]), pos=1)
  arrows(Y[N+1,1], Y[N+1,2],
         Y[N+1,1]+LV(Y[N+1,])[1], Y[N+1,2]+LV(Y[N+1,])[2],
         length=.1, lwd=2)
  title(paste("The fourth-order RungeKutta method (h = ",h,")", sep=""))
}

The result is further improvement. RK4 with \(h=3\) looks just like the midpoint method with \(h=2\).

Computational efficiency

The midpoint and RK4 improve the accuracy of linear approximation through additional computation (i.e., more calls of \(f\) to get better slopes).

Does the improved accuracy justify the additional computation, or should we just use the Euler scheme and reduce \(h\)?

Specifically, here is the trade-off:

Method Error per step \(f\) calls per step
Euler \(O(h^2)\) 1
Midpoint \(O(h^3)\) 2
RK4 \(O(h^5)\) 4

It is hard to give a definite answer based only on this information because many factors affect the answer. For example:

  • While \(f\) calls are given by specific numbers, \(O(n)\) is by definition silent on scalar multiples.
  • Cumulative errors depend on how many steps we run.
  • Available computational resource is a key determinant.

To get a feel, lets conduct a simple numerical experiment.

An ODE to solve is \(\frac{dy}{dt} = -y\) with \(y(0)=1\), to which we know the analytical solution \(y(t)=e^{-t}\). We examine how many \(f\) calls are required to achieve \(|\hat{y}(1)-y(1)|\leq\epsilon\) by repeatedly reducing \(h\) by half. We test six tolerance values: \(\epsilon\in\{10^{-1}, 10^{-2}, 10^{-3}, 10^{-4}, 10^{-5}, 10^{-6}\}\).

# parameters
methods <- list(euler, midpoint, RK4)
f <- function(y) -y # RHS of the ODE
y1.true <- exp(-1) # y(t=1)
epsilons <- 10^(-(1:6))

re <- matrix(nrow=3, ncol=length(epsilons)) # for results

y.N <- function(Y) Y[length(Y)] # pick up the last row of the matrix Y
run <- function(j, col, epsilon) {
  h <- 1
  method <- methods[[j]]
  y <- y.N(method(f, y0=1, h=h, N=1/h))
  while (abs(y - y1.true) > epsilon) {
    h <- h/2
    y <- y.N(method(f, y0=1, h=h, N=1/h))
  }
  # 1, 2, and 4 evaluations per step in method 1, 2, and 3 respectively.
  return(2^(j-1)/h)
}

for (col in 1:length(epsilons)) {
  epsilon <- epsilons[col]
  
  for (i in 1:3) {
    re[i,col] <- run(i, col, epsilon)
  }
}

The result is summarised below.

plot(-log(epsilons), log(re[1,]), type='b',
     pch=1, xlab = '-log(epsilon)', ylab = 'log(f calls)')
lines(-log(epsilons), log(re[2,]), type='b', pch=2)
lines(-log(epsilons), log(re[3,]), type='b', pch=3)
legend('topleft', legend = c('Euler', 'Midpoint', 'RK4'),
       pch = c(1, 2, 3), inset = .1)

\(\epsilon\) \(10^{-1}\) \(10^{-2}\) \(10^{-3}\) \(10^{-4}\) \(10^{-5}\) \(10^{-6}\)
Euler 4 32 256 2048 32768 262144
Midpoint 4 8 32 64 256 512
RK4 4 4 8 16 32 32

In this experiment, as expected, RK4 performs uniformly better than the others.
